## Workstation Security Model

<!-- Remove this section if your dev machine is not segregated -->

### Purpose

The development workstation is a **segregated machine** dedicated to AI-assisted coding. Its security model ensures: **zero credentials at rest, physical hardware required for all signing/auth operations**.

### Why Segregation

AI coding agents have terminal access. A compromised agent could:
- Read stored credentials from keychain, environment, or config files
- Use persistent OAuth tokens to delete repositories or push malicious code
- Exfiltrate personal data if personal accounts are accessible

### Identity Model

| Rule | Detail |
|------|--------|
| **Permitted account** | `<SEGREGATED_ACCOUNT>` |
| **Forbidden account** | `<PERSONAL_ACCOUNT>` — no tokens, no keychain entries, nothing |
| **Git identity** | `<GIT_USER>` / `<GIT_EMAIL>` |
| **Password vault** | `<VAULT_ACCOUNT>` on `<VAULT_SERVER>` (separate from personal vault) |

### Authentication Layers

#### Layer 1: Git Operations (Hardware Security Key — touch required)

All git commits and pushes require physical security key touch. Shell wrappers bypass `ssh-agent` and talk to the key directly:

| Operation | Wrapper | What happens |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `git commit` (signing) | `git-ssh-sign` → `ssh-keygen` | Key LED blinks, touch to sign |
| `git push/pull` (auth) | `git-ssh-auth` → `ssh` | Key LED blinks, touch to authenticate |

**Key**: `<SSH_KEY_PATH>` (ed25519-sk resident key, application `<FIDO_APP_NAME>`). Registered on `<SEGREGATED_ACCOUNT>` as both authentication and signing key.

**Why wrappers**: AI coding tools run git as subprocesses with no TTY. The macOS `ssh-agent` can't prompt for FIDO2 touch in non-TTY contexts. The wrappers unset `SSH_AUTH_SOCK` to force direct key communication.

**Protection**: A compromised agent cannot sign commits or push code without physical touch. The private key never leaves the hardware.

#### Layer 2: Password Vault (Keychain + FIDO2 WebAuthn)

| Component | Method |
|-----------|--------|
| Master password storage | OS Keychain (encrypted at rest, no silent app access) |
| Master password retrieval | Helper command → clipboard, auto-clears in N seconds |
| 2FA (full login) | Hardware security key FIDO2 WebAuthn (physical touch) |
| Vault timeout | N minutes → Lock |

#### Layer 3: GitHub CLI (Ephemeral Sessions)

The `gh` CLI is **not kept logged in**. OAuth tokens grant broad `repo` scope which would allow a compromised agent to delete repositories.

| Command | Purpose |
|---------|---------|
| `gh-session login` | Authenticate via browser, store token temporarily |
| `gh-session logout` | Revoke token AND scrub OS keychain entries |
| `gh-session status` | Verify no persistent tokens remain |

**Flow**: Login → do PR/issue work → logout. No persistent token survives between sessions.

### Threat Model

| Threat | Mitigated? | How |
|--------|-----------|-----|
| Agent reads stored passwords | Yes | No passwords on disk (Keychain requires login password, silent access blocked) |
| Agent pushes malicious code | Yes | Git push requires physical key touch |
| Agent signs malicious commits | Yes | Git signing requires physical key touch |
| Agent deletes repos via API | Yes | No persistent `gh` CLI token (ephemeral sessions) |
| Agent reads password vault | Partial | Vault locks after timeout; clipboard clears after N seconds |
| Agent accesses personal accounts | Yes | No personal account credentials exist on machine |
| Agent modifies git wrappers | Low risk | Modified wrapper can't forge signatures (private key on hardware) |

### Credential Lifecycle

```
Security key plugged in:
  → Git operations: touch per commit/push (no stored credential)
  → Vault: helper → clipboard → auto-clear (master password in Keychain)
  → gh CLI: login → work → logout → keychain scrubbed

Security key removed:
  → Git operations: fail (no signing, no push)
  → Vault: locked after timeout
  → gh CLI: not logged in
  → SSH to infra: works (uses regular ed25519 key, no hardware key needed)
```

### Key Generation

<!-- Adjust command for your security key and identity -->

```bash
SSH_SK_PROVIDER=<SK_PROVIDER_PATH> ssh-keygen \
  -t ed25519-sk \
  -O resident \
  -O application=ssh:<APP_NAME> \
  -C "<KEY_COMMENT>" \
  -f ~/.ssh/<KEY_FILENAME> \
  -N ""
```

**FIDO2 flag behavior**:

| Flag | Behavior | Use case |
|------|----------|----------|
| (default) | Touch + may require PIN | Standard security |
| `-O no-touch-required` | Silent (no LED, no touch) | Automated/headless only |
| `-O verify-required` | Touch + PIN every time | Maximum security |

Generate with the same `ssh-keygen` binary used by wrappers for consistent flag behavior.

